In the CPI's Web UI, create a new Integration Flow artifact. Give it a name that indicates its purpose (e.g., "UserAuthentication").
Define a sender for the Integration Flow. This could be an HTTPS connection that allows other systems to send HTTP POST requests to the integration flow.
Add a Content Modifier step to extract the username and password from the incoming HTTP request. You'll use XPath or JSONPath expressions to do this, depending on the format of incoming request.
Add a Request-Reply step to send the username and password to the backend system for verification. You'll need to define a receiver for this step that points to the backend system.
Add a Groovy Script step to handle the response from the backend system. This script will check the response and set the HTTP response code and body accordingly.
Add an End Event to the integration flow. This will send the HTTP response back to the sender.
Once integration flow is set up, deploy it to CPI runtime environment.
Test the integration flow by sending an HTTP POST request with a username and password and checking the response.
